The Dataset

The SUDMEX TMS dataset is a randomised, double-blind, longitudinal trial involving 54 Mexican patients with CUD undergoing rTMS treatment. Data were collected at five time points over the course of a year and included demographic, clinical, cognitive and multimodal MRI measures (structural, functional and diffusion) Angeles-Valdez, et.al., 2024.

Save the Plots

Steps:

1- Create your plot . 2- Save the plot to your environment using <-.
3- Use the following commands to save your plot to a file.

plotA <- ggstatsplot::ggbetweenstats(data1, x = group, y = tot_score, type = "parametric")
plotB <- ggstatsplot::ggbetweenstats(data1, x = group, y = cog, type = "parametric")

ggsave("../plots/PlotA.png", plotA, dpi= 300, height = 8, width = 10)
ggsave("../plots/PlotB.tiff", plotB, dpi= 300, height = 8, width = 10)

Combine plot

1- Create your individual plots and assign them to separate variables.
2- Combine the plots using ggarrange().
3- Save your plot.

library(ggpubr)
combined_plot <- ggarrange(plotA, plotB, ncol = 2, nrow = 1,
                                     labels = c("A", "B"))

ggsave("../plots/combined_plot.png", combined_plot, dpi= 300, height = 8, width = 10)

What is t-test?

A t-test is a statistical method used to compare the means of two groups.

data_t_test <- data_BIS %>% 
  filter(stage=="T0")%>%  
  mutate(group = case_when(group == 1 ~ "SHAM", 
                           group ==  2 ~ "TMS"))

t.test(tot_score~group,
       #alternative = c("two.sided", "less", "greater"),
       conf.level = 0.95, 
       #paired = TRUE,
       data = data_t_test)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  tot_score by group
## t = -0.53238, df = 47.125, p-value = 0.597
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group SHAM and group TMS is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11.793859   6.857627
## sample estimates:
## mean in group SHAM  mean in group TMS 
##           62.56522           65.03333

Tip: Familiarise yourself with the limitations of your data and the limitations of statistical analysis..

What is Correlation?

Correlation Analysis is statistical method that is used to discover if there is a relationship between two variables/datasets

Load R packages

library(pacman)
pacman::p_load(tidyverse,corrplot) 
# Data arrangement

data_BIS2 <- data_BIS %>% select(rid,group,stage,cog,mot,nonp,tot_score) %>%  
  filter(stage=="T0") %>%  
  select(-rid, -group, -stage)
Corr_matrix <-  cor(data_BIS2)

corrplot(Corr_matrix, method = 'number', ) # colorful number

corrplot(Corr_matrix,  method = 'color', order = 'alphabet')

testRes = cor.mtest(data_BIS2, conf.level = 0.95)
corrplot(Corr_matrix, p.mat = testRes$p, method = "circle", sig.level = 0.05,addCoef.col ='black')

data_BIS3 <- data_BIS2 %>%  
  mutate(new = runif(n(), min = 5, max = 50)) %>%  
  as.data.frame() %>%  
  cor()

testRes = cor.mtest(data_BIS3, conf.level = 0.95)
corrplot(data_BIS3, p.mat = testRes$p, method = "circle", sig.level = 0.05,addCoef.col ='black')

Change the color

Example

  corrplot(Corr_matrix, method = 'square',  type = 'lower', diag = FALSE,  col = COL2('PiYG'))

What is Regression ?

A linear model specifies a linear relationship between a dependent variable and independent variables, the model takes the form:

\(Y ∼ β0 + Xβ1 + ϵ\)
\(Y ∼ N ormal(μ, σ)\)

data_B <- data_BIS %>%
  filter(stage=="T0") %>%  
  select(rid, BIS_tot=tot_score)  

data_H <- data_HDRS %>%

Remember !!

A crucial aspect when building regression models is to evaluate the quality of modelfit.

# Load package 
library(performance)

Check assuptioms

Linearity:

Purpose: Checks if the relationship between predictors and the outcome is linear.
Interpretation: Residuals should be randomly scattered. If most points are around the horizontal line, linearity is likely satisfied.

Homoscedasticity:

Purpose: Verifies if residuals have constant variance.
Interpretation: Residuals should display no clear pattern and be equally spread, indicating constant variance.

Normality of Residuals:

Purpose: Examines if residuals are normally distributed.
Interpretation: Residuals should fall along the reference line in the Q-Q plot. Deviations suggest a departure from normality.

Check assuptioms

performance::check_normality(model2)
## OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.861).
performance::check_heteroscedasticity(model2)
## OK: Error variance appears to be homoscedastic (p = 0.942).

Check for Homogeneity of Variance (Homoscedasticity)

performance::check_model(model2)

Perfomance of the model

model_performance(model2)
## # Indices of model performance
## 
## AIC     |    AICc |     BIC |    R2 | R2 (adj.) |   RMSE |  Sigma
